NL Golden Jubilee celebtration today; Comm Landis, NL Pres Heydler, Gov Fuller, Mayor Curley, Braves VP Fuchs at ceremony raising the pennant celebrating 50 years of baseball.  Braves and Cubs were charter members of the original league in 1876 and are the only clubs which can boast an unbroken history in the organization. Also in attendance: players George Wright, Jack Manning, John Morrell, and Tom Bond, Umpire Bill McLean, and former Braves owner W. Conant.1925BSN.EVN.regular.comment.csv"

ej,smite106,P,riglc901,Arguing with spectator $Earl Smith was ejected for fighting with a fan. Angered by a continuing verbal attack by the fan in a box seat, Smith, who had just backed up the play at 1B, quickly climbed into the stands and struck the offender. 'That gent was on me all day.  He called me all sorts of names.  When I decided to go after him, I asked him to take off his glasses.  He took them off and I socked him in the  side of the neck.' Teammates ran to his assistance and a near riot ensued. Police and the umpires quelled the disturbance. As Smith neared the park exit, another irate rooter threw a chair that struck him, inflicting a gash on his forehead which required medical attention.  NY Times version: The trouble started when Smith ran toward the grandstand for a foul fly which he failed to catch.  He became embroiled in an argument with W.J. Lewis of Boston, a spectator.  They were preparing to 'mix' when onlookers said Smith struck the spectator a glancing blow.  Police and others intervened and Smith was ordered from the game as the crowd swarmed onto the field.  As he passed down the steps to the visiting team's quarters beneath the grandstand, a chair, thrown by an unidentified spectator, landed on top of him.  The police had difficulty for a time in handling the crowd. Boston Globe: The heckling of Smith began after he had run into Burrus at first base.  For this Smith was not to blame.1925BSN.EVN.regular.comment.csv"

Ump Rigler called Rawlings out after Johnny had slid past the plate.  The play was not close as far as the position of the ball was concerned, but the alert O'Neil took the bounding sphere and tagged Rawlings after the whole play seemed to be over.  Rigler, in the opinion of many, was tricked by O'Neil's stunt.  From the press box Rawling's foot seemed to get almost half of the plate.  The unexpected ruling threw the Pirates in an uproar.1925BSN.EVN.regular.comment.csv"
